# Impacts of Modern Economic Systems on Human Biology and Cognition

Modern industrialized economies have dramatically altered human lifestyles and environments, with far-reaching effects on our biology and cognitive health. Widespread urbanization, high population densities, industrial pollution, synthetic chemicals, and globalized food systems characterize modern life. These factors, often intertwined with economic growth and technological progress, have introduced **novel environmental exposures** that can modify our DNA activity (epigenetics), shape neurodevelopment, influence mental health, and shift disease patterns. Researchers increasingly find that the cumulative “**exposome**” of modern life — the sum of all exposures from conception onward — leaves measurable biological imprints and health consequences ([
            Environmental Epigenetics and Its Implication on Disease Risk and Health Outcomes - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4021822/#:~:text=endocrine%20disruptors%2C%20tobacco%20smoke%2C%20polycyclic,the%20prescription%20of%20effective%20countermeasures)) ([Our epigenome is influenced by our habitat and lifestyle | Institut Pasteur](https://www.pasteur.fr/en/our-epigenome-influenced-our-habitat-and-lifestyle#:~:text=These%20results%20partly%20explain%20why,more%20prone%20to%20the%20development)). In this overview, we examine peer-reviewed studies on how key features of modern economic systems (pollution, synthetic chemicals, urban living, stress, and diet) affect human biology at the genetic, neurological, and cognitive levels, often in comparison to pre-industrial conditions.

## Air Pollution: Epigenetic Damage and Cognitive Decline

One hallmark of modern economies is industrial **air pollution**, from vehicle emissions, power plants, and urban smog. **Chronic exposure to polluted air has been strongly linked to health damage** ranging from cardiovascular and respiratory diseases to neurological decline. The World Health Organization estimates that in 2012, around *7 million* premature deaths (one in eight globally) were attributable to air pollution, making it the world’s largest environmental health risk ([
	7 million premature deaths annually linked to air pollution
](https://www.who.int/news/item/25-03-2014-7-million-premature-deaths-annually-linked-to-air-pollution#:~:text=25%20March%202014%20,could%20save%20millions%20of%20lives)). Polluted air (especially fine particulate matter, PM₂.₅) contributes to higher rates of **stroke, heart disease, lung cancer, and chronic lung conditions** ([
	7 million premature deaths annually linked to air pollution
](https://www.who.int/news/item/25-03-2014-7-million-premature-deaths-annually-linked-to-air-pollution#:~:text=In%20particular%2C%20the%20new%20data,and%20chronic%20obstructive%20pulmonary%20diseases)), diseases that were far rarer before industrialization.

At the biological level, air pollution exerts its effects partly through **epigenetic modifications**. Particulate pollutants can trigger changes in DNA methylation and other gene regulatory marks without altering the DNA sequence. For example, research indicates that **airborne particles cause “epigenetic damage”** – aberrant DNA methylation and microRNA changes – that can promote diseases like cancer, fibrosis, metabolic disorders and even neurodegeneration ([Frontiers | Epigenetic mechanisms of particulate matter exposure: air pollution and hazards on human health](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/genetics/articles/10.3389/fgene.2023.1306600/full#:~:text=diseases%20by%20altered%20epigenetic%20regulation,of%20early%20detection%20for%20novel)) ([Frontiers | Epigenetic mechanisms of particulate matter exposure: air pollution and hazards on human health](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/genetics/articles/10.3389/fgene.2023.1306600/full#:~:text=Epigenetic%20damage%20is%20one%20of,Previous%20research%20has%20demonstrated)). Such epigenetic changes may serve as biomarkers of an individual’s pollution exposure and early indicators of disease risk ([Frontiers | Epigenetic mechanisms of particulate matter exposure: air pollution and hazards on human health](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/genetics/articles/10.3389/fgene.2023.1306600/full#:~:text=diseases%20by%20altered%20epigenetic%20regulation,of%20early%20detection%20for%20novel)). **Neurotoxicity** from air pollution is also a growing concern: fine particles can penetrate the bloodstream and even the brain, where they induce chronic inflammation. This neuroinflammation leads to **synapse dysfunction and neuron loss** in various brain regions, impairing cognitive, motor, and emotional processes ([Frontiers | Epigenetic mechanisms of particulate matter exposure: air pollution and hazards on human health](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/genetics/articles/10.3389/fgene.2023.1306600/full#:~:text=apoptosis%2C%20synapse%20dysfunction%2C%20and%20neurodegeneration,response%20of%20the%20host%20tissue)). Consistently, epidemiological studies show that long-term pollution exposure correlates with **accelerated cognitive decline and higher dementia incidence** in exposed populations ([A critical review of the epidemiological evidence of effects of air ...](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S004896972037265X#:~:text=A%20critical%20review%20of%20the,imaging%20studies)). In essence, modern urban air pollution is **“getting under the skin” and into the brain**, altering gene expression and aging the brain faster than seen in cleaner pre-industrial environments.

## Synthetic Chemicals: Endocrine Disruption and Biological Shifts

Modern economies have introduced tens of thousands of **synthetic chemicals** (pesticides, plastics, industrial compounds) into the environment since the mid-20th century. (Indeed, over **140,000 new chemicals** and pesticides have been synthesized and released since the 1950s ([Toxic Chemicals in Everyday Life - Environmental Audit Committee](https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201719/cmselect/cmenvaud/1805/180504.htm#:~:text=Toxic%20Chemicals%20in%20Everyday%20Life,5%2C000%20chemicals%20produced%20in)), exposures largely absent in pre-industrial times.) Many of these compounds act as **endocrine-disrupting chemicals (EDCs)**, interfering with hormones that regulate development, metabolism, and brain function. The human **nervous system is highly vulnerable** to such chemical disruptions. According to the Endocrine Society, EDC exposures are linked to **decreased IQ and more neurodevelopmental problems** in children, along with other cognitive and behavioral issues ([Impact of EDCs on Neurological and Behavioral Systems | Endocrine Society](https://www.endocrine.org/topics/edc/what-edcs-are/common-edcs/neurological#:~:text=The%20World%20Health%20Organization%2C%20the,problems%2C%20and%20other%20neurocognitive%20conditions)). For instance, polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), once widely used in industry, have strong associations with **neurodevelopmental disorders**, and even remote communities (e.g. in the Arctic) with high PCB buildup show increased cognitive deficits like lower attention and memory performance ([Impact of EDCs on Neurological and Behavioral Systems | Endocrine Society](https://www.endocrine.org/topics/edc/what-edcs-are/common-edcs/neurological#:~:text=The%20danger%20extends%20to%20places,memory%2C%20and%20fine%20motor%20skills)) ([Impact of EDCs on Neurological and Behavioral Systems | Endocrine Society](https://www.endocrine.org/topics/edc/what-edcs-are/common-edcs/neurological#:~:text=Which%20EDCs%20are%20the%20culprits%3F,effects%20of%20many%20common%20EDCs)). Another example is lead (historically added to gasoline and paint), which was a byproduct of industrial economies and caused widespread **IQ reductions and neurological damage** in children until it was phased out.

Beyond direct neurotoxicity, synthetic chemicals often induce **epigenetic changes** that alter biological pathways. Environmental epigenetics research has shown that a variety of modern pollutants – **endocrine disruptors, heavy metals, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs)** from fossil fuels, etc. – can **trigger DNA methylation changes in exposed individuals ([
            Environmental Epigenetics and Its Implication on Disease Risk and Health Outcomes - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4021822/#:~:text=Environmental%20factors%20such%20as%20endocrine,many%20complex%20diseases%2C%20including%20cancer)). These epigenetic alterations have been observed in many diseases** (cancers, immune disorders, etc.), linking toxic exposures to heightened disease risk ([
            Environmental Epigenetics and Its Implication on Disease Risk and Health Outcomes - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4021822/#:~:text=Environmental%20factors%20such%20as%20endocrine,many%20complex%20diseases%2C%20including%20cancer)). Worryingly, some chemical exposures may even have **transgenerational effects**: animal studies demonstrate that certain EDCs can cause heritable epigenetic modifications. For example, experiments with fungicides and plastics (vinclozolin, BPA) showed altered sperm epigenetic patterns that led to fertility problems and disease in offspring for multiple generations ([
            Environmental Epigenetics and Its Implication on Disease Risk and Health Outcomes - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4021822/#:~:text=transgenerational%20actions%20of%20endocrine%20disruptors,programming%20of%20the%20germ%20line)). In humans, the idea of chemical exposures “reprogramming” biology is supported by findings like prenatal toxin exposure correlating with later-life disease in children and grandchildren.

Modern synthetic chemicals also contribute to the **“diseases of civilization.”** Many industrial chemicals in our air, water, and food act as **metabolic disruptors or “obesogens.”** Evidence is growing that compounds such as bisphenol-A (BPA, in plastics), organochlorine pesticides, and phthalates (in cosmetics and plastics) can perturb metabolism and promote **obesity, diabetes, and related disorders** ([
            Environmental Epigenetics and Its Implication on Disease Risk and Health Outcomes - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4021822/#:~:text=neuroendocrine%20systems%20and%20behavior%20,2011)). These chemicals may alter epigenetic regulators of fat cell development and appetite, predisposing individuals to weight gain. The rise of metabolic diseases in the 20th century thus has an environmental component: unlike our pre-industrial ancestors, we are now chronically exposed to low doses of synthetic chemicals that subtly **shift hormonal and genetic signals**, increasing the burden of chronic disease.

## Urbanization, Population Density, and Mental Health

Rapid **urbanization** is another defining feature of modern economic systems. Over half of the world’s population now lives in cities, a stark contrast to pre-industrial societies that were predominantly rural. **High-density urban living** brings benefits like improved infrastructure and economies of scale, but it also introduces chronic stressors: crowding, noise, social isolation amid crowds, and often higher crime or competition – all of which can affect mental well-being and brain development. **Psychiatric epidemiology** has repeatedly found that **city living is associated with higher risks of mental disorders**. Notably, being born or raised in an urban environment roughly *doubles* the risk of developing schizophrenia in adulthood compared to being raised in a rural area ([
            Brain Structure Correlates of Urban Upbringing, an Environmental Risk Factor for Schizophrenia - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4266290/#:~:text=schizophrenia,3%29%2C%20empirical)) ([Associations between the urban environment and psychotic ...](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0920996423002827#:~:text=Associations%20between%20the%20urban%20environment,Whether%20urbanicity)). This striking two-fold increase, observed in studies across different countries, suggests some aspect of **city life acts as an environmental risk factor for psychosis**. Leading hypotheses implicate the social stress of high-density living – for example, chronic exposure to **social evaluative stress, inequality, and possibly viral exposures or pollution** – which may interact with genetic predispositions.

Neuroscience studies provide clues to how urban stress gets “into the brain.” A landmark study of healthy young adults found that **growing up in a city was correlated with differences in brain structure**: individuals with urban childhoods showed reduced gray matter volume in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, a region involved in stress regulation and executive function ([
            Brain Structure Correlates of Urban Upbringing, an Environmental Risk Factor for Schizophrenia - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4266290/#:~:text=possible%20morphological%20correlate%20of%20urban,Previous%20data%20linking%20functional)). They also showed hyper-reactivity of the amygdala and cingulate regions during social stress, indicating a sensitized stress response. These neural effects align with the idea that **early-life urban stressors can calibrate (or dysregulate) the developing brain**, potentially making one more susceptible to mental illness ([
            Brain Structure Correlates of Urban Upbringing, an Environmental Risk Factor for Schizophrenia - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4266290/#:~:text=Furthermore%2C%20we%20detected%20a%20negative,life%20urbanicity%20could)). Supporting this, recent UK Biobank research that modeled complex urban exposures found that a profile of **social deprivation, air pollution, and dense urban form correlated significantly with mood disorder symptoms**, mediated by brain volume changes in regions tied to emotion and reward processing ([Effects of urban living environments on mental health in adults | Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02365-w#:~:text=of%20156%2C075%20participants%20from%20the,accessibility%20were%20negatively%20correlated%20with)). In that study, genes related to stress responses (like the **CRHR1** cortisol receptor gene) moderated the brain changes, suggesting gene–environment interaction where those with certain genetics are more affected by urban stress ([Effects of urban living environments on mental health in adults | Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02365-w#:~:text=and%20psychiatric%20symptoms,profile%20was%20correlated%20with%20an)). Conversely, **urban design factors like access to green spaces emerged as protective**, correlating with lower anxiety symptoms and healthier emotion-regulation circuits ([Effects of urban living environments on mental health in adults | Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02365-w#:~:text=and%20moderated%20by%20genes%20enriched,groups%20through%20distinct%20neurobiological%20pathways)). 

In summary, **modern urban environments can amplify certain mental health risks** through chronic social stress and environmental burdens. Compared to the smaller communities of the past, today’s megacities expose inhabitants to a constant background of noise, crowds, and complexity that our brains and social systems may struggle to adapt to. This is evidenced by higher rates of anxiety, depression, and psychosis in densely populated cities (relative to more bucolic settings) and by measurable differences in brain structure and function linked to urban stress exposure.

- *Higher psychosis risk in cities:* Large population studies have found up to **2× higher incidence of schizophrenia in the most urbanized areas** compared to rural areas ([Associations between the urban environment and psychotic ...](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0920996423002827#:~:text=Associations%20between%20the%20urban%20environment,Whether%20urbanicity)). This urban effect on psychosis is one of the most robust associations in psychiatric epidemiology, pointing to city-specific stressors.
- *Mood and anxiety disorders:* Dense, high-stress urban neighborhoods (with more pollution, noise, and social adversity) are associated with **increased depression and anxiety symptom rates**, as shown by UK Biobank analyses correlating urban exposure profiles with mental health ([Effects of urban living environments on mental health in adults | Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02365-w#:~:text=of%20156%2C075%20participants%20from%20the,accessibility%20were%20negatively%20correlated%20with)). Brain imaging indicates urban stress can overactivate fear and emotion centers of the brain ([
            Brain Structure Correlates of Urban Upbringing, an Environmental Risk Factor for Schizophrenia - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4266290/#:~:text=Furthermore%2C%20we%20detected%20a%20negative,life%20urbanicity%20could)).
- *Protective factors:* Not all aspects of cities are negative – the presence of **green parks, trees, and accessible open spaces** can mitigate stress. Individuals in greener urban areas report lower anxiety and show brain patterns indicative of better emotion regulation ([Effects of urban living environments on mental health in adults | Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02365-w#:~:text=and%20moderated%20by%20genes%20enriched,groups%20through%20distinct%20neurobiological%20pathways)). This highlights that thoughtful urban planning can buffer some of the mental health impacts of high-density living.

## Chronic Stress and Socioeconomic Pressures

Modern economic structures not only shape our physical environment, but also our **psychosocial environment**. The fast pace of life, work pressures, long work hours, economic inequality, and constant information flow in modern societies contribute to pervasive **chronic stress**. While acute stress responses are natural and adaptive, chronic unrelenting stress can become toxic, leading to what scientists call **“allostatic load”** – the cumulative wear-and-tear on bodily systems. Allostatic load represents the overload of multiple organ systems (cardiovascular, immune, metabolic, etc.) under chronic stress, and it is strongly linked to **poorer health outcomes and earlier disease onset** ([Allostatic Load and Its Impact on Health: A Systematic Review - PubMed](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32799204/#:~:text=Conclusions%3A%20%20The%20findings%20indicate,and%20clinimetric%20criteria%20is%20recommended)). In effect, the **economic and social pressures** of modern life (e.g. job insecurity, high competition, overcrowding, or poverty) can translate into **biological strain** that was less common in pre-industrial contexts where social structures were different.

At the molecular level, chronic stress has **epigenetic consequences** that provide a link between psychological environment and gene expression. For instance, studies have examined DNA methylation in individuals of differing socioeconomic status (SES) as a marker of chronic stress exposure. One multi-ethnic study found that **low childhood SES was associated with distinct DNA methylation patterns in stress-related genes** like *AVP* (arginine vasopressin), *FKBP5* (a regulator of cortisol receptors), and *OXTR* (oxytocin receptor), as well as in immune/inflammatory genes ([Life course socioeconomic status and DNA methylation in genes related to stress reactivity and inflammation: The multi-ethnic study of atherosclerosis - PubMed](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26295359/#:~:text=non,In)). Low adult SES similarly affected methylation of stress and inflammation genes, suggesting that growing up and living in poverty imprints a biological “memory” of stress on the genome ([Life course socioeconomic status and DNA methylation in genes related to stress reactivity and inflammation: The multi-ethnic study of atherosclerosis - PubMed](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26295359/#:~:text=non,In)). Such epigenetic changes could alter how the body handles stress hormones or inflammation, potentially increasing risks for mental illness and chronic diseases (since *FKBP5* and *OXTR* relate to anxiety/trauma responses, and inflammation underlies many diseases). Other research on workplace stress and daily hassles has likewise found that **chronic psychosocial stress can modify epigenetic markers in the brain and blood**, including genes like the serotonin transporter (*SLC6A4*), *BDNF* (brain-derived neurotrophic factor), and even the enzymes that control DNA methylation ([Frontiers | Epigenetics Underlying Susceptibility and Resilience Relating to Daily Life Stress, Work Stress, and Socioeconomic Status](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychiatry/articles/10.3389/fpsyt.2020.00163/full#:~:text=choreography%20of%20gene%E2%80%93environment%20interactions%20with,studies%20including%20the%20serotonin%20transporter)). These changes can affect neurotransmitter levels and neuroplasticity, providing a mechanism for how sustained stress elevates risk of depression, anxiety, or PTSD.

Over time, the accumulation of stress-induced changes can accelerate aging itself. Scientists measuring **“epigenetic age”** (via DNA methylation clocks) observe that individuals under higher chronic stress or from disadvantaged backgrounds often show **advanced biological aging** compared to their chronological age ([Socioeconomic Status, Lifestyle, and DNA Methylation Age Among ...](https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamanetworkopen/fullarticle/2821612#:~:text=Socioeconomic%20Status%2C%20Lifestyle%2C%20and%20DNA,by%20the%20DunedinPACE%20epigenetic%20clock)). This means their cells bear molecular hallmarks of older age, consistent with the idea that stress wears down the body faster. In modern societies, disparities in economic and social conditions thus become embodied as health disparities. Someone in a **high-stress urban poverty** situation may have a higher allostatic load and epigenetic age than a same-aged person in a low-stress environment, translating into higher rates of hypertension, diabetes, depression, and other conditions. In contrast, historical or non-industrial populations living in tight-knit communities with less chronic work/urban stress likely experienced far less allostatic load (though they faced other acute stressors like infections or food scarcity). The biology of stress reminds us that **economic structures – whether they foster social safety and balance or relentless pressure – directly shape human physiology** through hormones and gene regulation.

## Modern Diet and Food Systems: Metabolic and Cognitive Effects

Economic development has radically transformed human **food systems**. Industrial agriculture, global food trade, and mass production have made calorie-dense, processed foods abundant and cheap in many societies – a sharp departure from the high-fiber, unrefined diets of most pre-industrial communities. As a result, modern populations consume significantly more **refined sugars, unhealthy fats, and synthetic additives**, contributing to a global epidemic of obesity and metabolic diseases. The **Western diet (WD)** pattern (rich in red meats, processed grains, sweets, and fats) has been directly implicated in so-called **“diseases of civilization”** like coronary heart disease, type 2 diabetes, and certain cancers, which were historically rare ([The western diet and lifestyle and diseases of civilization | RRCC](https://www.dovepress.com/the-western-diet-and-lifestyle-and-diseases-of-civilization-peer-reviewed-fulltext-article-RRCC#:~:text=RRCC%20www,epithelial%20cell%20cancers%2C%20autoimmune)). The World Health Organization now considers obesity and overweight as an escalating *pandemic* of the 21st century, major risk factors behind multiple chronic diseases ([Frontiers | Western Diet: Implications for Brain Function and Behavior](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.564413/full#:~:text=Obesity%20and%20overweight%20are%20characterized,Xu%20et%20al)).

Beyond the well-known impacts on body weight and cardiovascular health, modern diets also affect **neurological and cognitive health**. High-fat, high-sugar diets have been linked in both animal models and human studies to **cognitive impairments and mood disorders** ([Frontiers | Western Diet: Implications for Brain Function and Behavior](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.564413/full#:~:text=The%20Western%20diet%20,stress%20modulates%20eating%20behavior%2C%20and)). Excess consumption of sugary/fatty foods can induce **neuroinflammation** – inflammation in the brain – and impair synaptic plasticity, particularly in regions like the hippocampus that are critical for memory. Over time, this contributes to memory deficits and an increased risk of dementia. Epidemiological studies find that midlife obesity is an independent risk factor for developing **Alzheimer’s disease and vascular dementia** later in life ([Frontiers | Western Diet: Implications for Brain Function and Behavior](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.564413/full#:~:text=which%20harms%20our%20health%20,Castro%20et%20al.%2C%202019)). In fact, some researchers warn that the Western diet and sedentary lifestyle may be **“setting the stage” for long-term neurocognitive decline** beginning in childhood ([Western Diet Consumption During Development: Setting the Stage ...](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7902933/#:~:text=Western%20Diet%20Consumption%20During%20Development%3A,lasting%20neurocognitive%20impairments)). One review noted that children who consume a Western-style diet early in life show **lasting neurocognitive impairments** as they age ([Western Diet Consumption During Development: Setting the Stage ...](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7902933/#:~:text=Western%20Diet%20Consumption%20During%20Development%3A,lasting%20neurocognitive%20impairments)), underscoring how modern food environments might be impacting brain development.

Mechanistically, modern diets influence the **brain–body axis** in several ways:

- **Gut–Brain Axis:** The Western diet alters the composition of the gut microbiota, the community of microbes in our intestines. This dysbiosis can produce metabolites and inflammation that impact brain function ([Frontiers | Western Diet: Implications for Brain Function and Behavior](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.564413/full#:~:text=The%20Western%20diet%20,stress%20modulates%20eating%20behavior%2C%20and)). Studies have shown links between diet-induced microbiome changes and behaviors like anxiety and impaired learning, highlighting how processed foods can indirectly modulate the brain via the gut.
- **Stress and Reward Pathways:** Highly processed, hyper-palatable foods can trigger **addictive-like eating behaviors** and disturb the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis (the central stress response system). Chronic intake of these foods may desensitize reward circuits and drive overeating while also raising cortisol levels, leading to a vicious cycle of **stress and emotional eating** ([Frontiers | Western Diet: Implications for Brain Function and Behavior](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.564413/full#:~:text=microbiota%2C%20influencing%20brain%20function%20by,current%20scientific%20evidence%20about%20the)). This HPA dysregulation is associated with increased anxiety and depressive-like symptoms in both animal experiments and humans who consume Western diets ([Frontiers | Western Diet: Implications for Brain Function and Behavior](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/psychology/articles/10.3389/fpsyg.2020.564413/full#:~:text=microbiota%2C%20influencing%20brain%20function%20by,current%20scientific%20evidence%20about%20the)).
- **Epigenetic Modifications:** Nutrient excess or imbalance can also **reprogram gene expression via epigenetics**. For example, high-fat/high-sugar diets have been shown to induce epigenetic changes in brain tissue and immune cells. Research in mice demonstrated that **chronic Western diet consumption led to DNA methylation changes in the frontal cortex**, affecting genes involved in synaptic function and cognitive performance ([
            Chronic consumption of a Western diet modifies the DNA methylation profile in the frontal cortex of mice - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5821526/#:~:text=match%20at%20L681%20associated%20with,decline%20observed%20in%20our%20mice)) ([
            Chronic consumption of a Western diet modifies the DNA methylation profile in the frontal cortex of mice - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5821526/#:~:text=associated%20with%20cognitive%20impairment78%E2%80%9381%2C%20and,decline%20observed%20in%20our%20mice)). Similarly, Western diets can modify epigenetic marks in immune cells (like monocytes), causing pro-inflammatory gene expression ([Global Impacts of Western Diet and Its Effects on Metabolism and Health: A Narrative Review](https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/15/12/2749#:~:text=,of%20genes%20related%20to%20the)). These diet-induced epigenetic shifts may contribute to systemic inflammation and insulin resistance, which can harm both body and brain. In short, the **modern food environment interacts with our genome**, potentially predisposing individuals to metabolic and neurological disorders that were virtually unseen in pre-industrial populations eating whole foods.

It’s worth noting that historical diets varied widely across cultures, but none resembled the ultra-processed, high-sugar diet common in today’s fast-paced economies. Studies of present-day hunter-gatherer or subsistence farming communities (analogous to pre-industrial diets) show **very low incidence of obesity, diabetes, and atherosclerotic disease** compared to Western populations ([The western diet and lifestyle and diseases of civilization | RRCC](https://www.dovepress.com/the-western-diet-and-lifestyle-and-diseases-of-civilization-peer-reviewed-fulltext-article-RRCC#:~:text=RRCC%20www,epithelial%20cell%20cancers%2C%20autoimmune)). When such communities shift to a more “Western” lifestyle and diet, they rapidly begin to exhibit the same chronic diseases. This illustrates how **economic-driven dietary patterns can override genetic predisposition**, producing new health outcomes via metabolic strain and even intergenerational effects (e.g. maternal high-fat diets during pregnancy can epigenetically affect offspring brain architecture ([Global Impacts of Western Diet and Its Effects on Metabolism and Health: A Narrative Review](https://www.mdpi.com/2072-6643/15/12/2749#:~:text=match%20at%20L2301%20al.%20Life,CrossRef))).

## Historical vs. Pre-Industrial Comparisons

**How did the health of people in pre-industrial societies differ from today’s, and what does that reveal about modern economic influences?** Broadly, pre-industrial humans faced threats like infectious diseases, malnutrition, and physical injuries, but they were *not* exposed to the intense cocktail of pollution, synthetic chemicals, and lifestyle stressors ubiquitous now. Consequently, certain diseases that are common today were virtually nonexistent or extremely rare historically:

- **Chronic “Diseases of Civilization”:** Conditions such as obesity, type 2 diabetes, coronary heart disease, and many cancers have exploded in prevalence alongside industrialization ([The western diet and lifestyle and diseases of civilization | RRCC](https://www.dovepress.com/the-western-diet-and-lifestyle-and-diseases-of-civilization-peer-reviewed-fulltext-article-RRCC#:~:text=RRCC%20www,epithelial%20cell%20cancers%2C%20autoimmune)). Paleopathological and epidemiological data suggest that these chronic inflammatory diseases were much less frequent in societies with traditional diets and lifestyles. Modern economic structures that allow excess calorie intake and physical inactivity have created **new disease burdens that our ancestors typically avoided** (instead, they contended with periodic famine or hard physical labor, which kept metabolic diseases at bay).
- **Environmental Toxins:** Pre-industrial populations did not have to contend with anthropogenic toxins like heavy metals from factories, EDCs in plastics, or pesticide residues. For example, **lead and PCBs** did not pollute pre-modern air or water; thus, historical peoples did not suffer the neurodevelopmental damage that 20th-century children exposed to leaded gasoline did. In modern times, even remote communities accumulate industrial pollutants (as noted with Arctic PCB contamination causing cognitive issues ([Impact of EDCs on Neurological and Behavioral Systems | Endocrine Society](https://www.endocrine.org/topics/edc/what-edcs-are/common-edcs/neurological#:~:text=The%20danger%20extends%20to%20places,memory%2C%20and%20fine%20motor%20skills))), a truly modern phenomenon. The absence of such pollutants in the past meant **cleaner biology** – no endocrine disruption, no smog-induced epigenetic mutations – and thus lower risk of related diseases.
- **Urban Stress vs. Traditional Lifestyles:** Most pre-industrial communities lived in smaller villages or nomadic bands, with strong social cohesion and a pace of life dictated by natural rhythms. They certainly experienced stress (e.g. war, natural disasters), but the **chronic day-to-day stress** (traffic jams, constant noise, financial anxiety) was far less. As a result, historical populations likely had lower allostatic load on average. A striking modern example comes from central Africa: researchers compared the same ethnic group living in different settings and found that **moving from a forest hunter-gatherer lifestyle to an urban environment changed the epigenome within a single generation** – specifically, urban dwellers showed different DNA methylation patterns in immune genes compared to their forest counterparts ([Our epigenome is influenced by our habitat and lifestyle | Institut Pasteur](https://www.pasteur.fr/en/our-epigenome-influenced-our-habitat-and-lifestyle#:~:text=The%20scientists%20began%20by%20comparing,functions%20of%20the%20immune%20system)). This suggests that the **“24/7” urban lifestyle quickly re-tunes biological systems** (like immunity and growth) in ways that pre-industrial lifestyles did not. Over generations, such epigenetic reprogramming (if coupled with genetic selection in historical times) led to different trait profiles; for instance, long-term farming vs. foraging lifestyles produced epigenetic and genetic differences related to body size and metabolism between populations ([Our epigenome is influenced by our habitat and lifestyle | Institut Pasteur](https://www.pasteur.fr/en/our-epigenome-influenced-our-habitat-and-lifestyle#:~:text=specific%20group%20of%20forest,functions%20of%20the%20immune%20system)). Today’s rapid urbanization is essentially fast-forwarding those changes, but with potential maladaptive outcomes (e.g. heightened inflammation or stress reactivity).
- **Mental Health Patterns:** While mental illnesses certainly existed in the past, some epidemiologists argue that *rates* of disorders like major depression and anxiety might be influenced by modern circumstances (though diagnosis differences complicate direct comparison). The high prevalence of anxiety disorders in the 21st century, for example, may relate to the fragmented social networks and information overload of modern economies. Traditional societies often had tight social support structures (extended family, tribe) that buffered psychological stress. Modern economic migration and urban life can erode these supports, possibly contributing to the observed **higher suicide and depression rates in urban, industrialized regions** versus more traditional rural regions in some studies ([Effects of urban living environments on mental health in adults | Nature Medicine](https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-023-02365-w#:~:text=of%20156%2C075%20participants%20from%20the,accessibility%20were%20negatively%20correlated%20with)). That said, historical comparisons are complex — pre-industrial life was often shorter and punctuated by trauma (which could also cause PTSD or depression). However, the **overall pattern of illness has shifted**: from predominantly acute, external threats (infections, starvation) to predominantly chronic, internally mediated illnesses (like stress-related and exposure-related diseases). This shift underscores how *economic development has fundamentally reorganized the landscape of health and disease*.

## Conclusion: Economic Structures as Hidden Determinants of Health

From the above, it is clear that the structures and byproducts of modern economic systems have become **embedded in our biology**. The push for industrial growth and urban concentration has led to polluted air and crowded cities, which in turn imprint on our lungs, hearts, and even gene expression patterns. The pursuit of convenience and profit in food production has filled our plates with ultra-processed fare, which our brains and metabolisms struggle to handle – resulting in epidemics of obesity and cognitive decline. The **stress of modern competitive economies** continuously activates our evolutionary “fight-or-flight” systems in a way that they were not designed for, leading to chronically elevated stress hormones and epigenetic aging. What we see in the mirror – rising rates of asthma in polluted cities, children with higher rates of neurodevelopmental disorders, adults facing burnout and depression, and populations facing unprecedented levels of chronic disease – is in many ways a **reflection of our economic choices** and policies.

On a hopeful note, recognizing that economic structures shape health outcomes allows for interventions at the policy level. For example, reducing air pollution through clean energy policies can yield not only environmental benefits but also **measurable improvements in population health and even cognitive development**. Similarly, regulating harmful chemicals, promoting whole foods over processed diets, designing “greener” cities with space for nature and community, and addressing income inequality and work-life balance are all systemic approaches that could alleviate the biological stress load on humans. The scientific literature increasingly supports this holistic view: health is not just a medical or genetic issue, but a social and economic one. Modern civilization has created new challenges for our minds and bodies, but with informed action, it can also create solutions – ensuring that progress in economic terms does not continue to come at the cost of our DNA integrity, brain health, and future generations’ well-being ([
            Environmental Epigenetics and Its Implication on Disease Risk and Health Outcomes - PMC
        ](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4021822/#:~:text=endocrine%20disruptors%2C%20tobacco%20smoke%2C%20polycyclic,the%20prescription%20of%20effective%20countermeasures)) ([Our epigenome is influenced by our habitat and lifestyle | Institut Pasteur](https://www.pasteur.fr/en/our-epigenome-influenced-our-habitat-and-lifestyle#:~:text=These%20results%20partly%20explain%20why,more%20prone%20to%20the%20development)).

